<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-instantaneous-rate-of-change" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Instantaneous Rate of Change</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine average rate of change and average rate of change at an instant from a graph
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To discover how to estimate the rate of change at a specific point on a curve by drawing a tangent line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Provide learners with curved graphs. Guide them in the technique of placing a ruler so it just touches the curve at a single point without crossing it.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert> Work in groups </alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                You are helping design a modern, energy-efficient greenhouse.
                The roof of the greenhouse follows a perfect parabolic curve defined by the equation <m>y = x^2</m>, where <m>y</m> is the height and <m>x</m> is the horizontal distance from the center.
            </p>
            <p>
                A support beam needs to be attached to the roof exactly at the point where <m>x = 2</m>.
                To ensure the joint is secure, the lead engineer needs to know the gradient (slope) of the roof at that specific point. 
                This gradient tells us "how fast <m>y</m> is changing" compared to <m>x</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A transparent ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A pencil or pen
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Carefully plot the graph of <m>y = x^2</m> for <m>x</m> from <m>0</m> to <m>4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the point <m>(2, 4)</m> on your graph.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using a transparent ruler, draw a line that <alert>just touches</alert> the curve at <m>(2, 4)</m>. This is the tangent line.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pick two points on this tangent line that are easy to read from the grid.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the gradient of the tangent line. What does this value tell you about the curve at <m>x = 2</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concept of instantaneous rate of change as the gradient of the tangent at a point.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Tangent Line:</alert> A tangent to a curve at a point is a straight line that touches the curve at that point and has the same gradient as the curve at that point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Instantaneous Rate:</alert> The gradient of the tangent gives the <alert>instantaneous rate of change</alert> (the rate of change at that specific instant).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <alert>instantaneous rate of change</alert> at a single point on a curve is the gradient of the <alert>tangent line</alert> at that point.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <term>Tangent line:</term> is a straight line that touches a curve at only one point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To find the gradient at an instant from a graph:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Identify the point on the curve.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw a tangent line at that point using a ruler.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Pick two points on the tangent line and calculate its gradient using <m>m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="img-tangent-illustration" width="65%">
            <latex-image label="Tangent Line Illustration">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-0.5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                    \draw[thick, blue, domain=0.5:4] plot (\x, {0.2*\x*\x + 1});
                    % Tangent
                    \coordinate (C) at (2, 1.8);
                    \draw[green!60!black, thick] (0.5, 0.6) -- (3.5, 3) node[right] {Tangent line};
                    \filldraw (C) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {Point of tangency};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Using a graph of <m>y = x^2</m>, estimate the gradient of the curve at the point <m>(2, 4)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the graph of <m>y = x^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a tangent line to the curve at the point <m>(2, 4)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Choose two points on the tangent line, for example <m>(1, 0)</m> and <m>(3, 8)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the gradient of the tangent:
                            <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{8 - 0}{3 - 1} = \frac{8}{2} = 4</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-example-tangent-inst" width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-1,0) grid (5,10);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,10) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:3.1] plot (\x, {\x*\x});
                        \draw[green!60!black, thick] (0.5, -2) -- (3.5, 10);
                        \filldraw (2,4) circle (2pt) node[above left] {$(2, 4)$};
                        \filldraw (1,0) circle (2pt) node[below left] {$(1, 0)$};
                        \filldraw (3,8) circle (2pt) node[right] {$(3, 8)$};
                        % Gradient triangle
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (1,0) -- (3,0) node[midway, below] {$\Delta x = 2$};
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (3,0) -- (3,8) node[midway, right] {$\Delta y = 8$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The estimated instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = 2</m> is <m>4</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The volume of water <m>V</m> (litres) in a leaking tank over time <m>t</m> (minutes) is given by <m>V = 100 - t^2</m>. Find the rate at which water is leaking exactly at <m>t = 5</m> minutes by drawing a tangent.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the graph of <m>V = 100 - t^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a tangent at the point <m>(5, 75)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pick points on the tangent like <m>(4, 85)</m> and <m>(6, 65)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Gradient = <m>\frac{65 - 85}{6 - 4} = \frac{-20}{2} = -10</m> litres/minute.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-example-volume-inst" width="65%">
                <description>Graph of V = 100 - t^2 with a tangent line and gradient triangle at t=5.</description>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm, y=0.05cm]
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, ystep=10, xstep=1] (0,0) grid (10,100);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (11,0) node[right] {$t$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-10) -- (0,110) node[above] {$V$};
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:10] plot (\x, {100 - \x*\x});
                        \draw[green!60!black, thick] (3, 95) -- (7, 55) node[right] {Tangent at $t=5$};
                        \filldraw (5,75) circle (3pt) node[above right] {$(5, 75)$};
                        % Gradient triangle
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (4,85) -- (6,85);
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (6,85) -- (6,65) node[midway, right] {$\Delta V = -20$};
                        \filldraw (4,85) circle (2pt);
                        \filldraw (6,65) circle (2pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Estimate the instantaneous rate of change of <m>y = x^3</m> at <m>x = 1</m> from a graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot <m>y = x^3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the tangent at <m>(1, 1)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Picking points on the tangent such as <m>(0, -2)</m> and <m>(2, 4)</m>:
                            <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{4 - (-2)}{2 - 0} = \frac{6}{2} = 3</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-example-cubic-tangent-inst" width="65%">
                <description>Graph of y = x^3 with a tangent line and gradient triangle at x=1.</description>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-2,-8) grid (2,8);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-2.5,0) -- (2.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-8.5) -- (0,8.5) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=-2.04:2.04] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x});
                        \draw[green!60!black, thick] (-1, -5) -- (2.5, 5.5);
                        \filldraw (1,1) circle (2pt) node[right] {$(1, 1)$};
                        % Gradient triangle
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (0,-2) -- (2,-2) node[midway, below] {$\Delta x = 2$};
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,-2) -- (2,4) node[midway, right] {$\Delta y = 6$};
                        \filldraw (0,-2) circle (2pt);
                        \filldraw (2,4) circle (2pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Sketch the graph of <m>y = 2x^2 + 1</m>. Estimate the gradient of the curve at <m>x = 1</m> by drawing a tangent.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    (The learner should draw the curve and a tangent at <m>(1, 3)</m>).
                    Picking points on the tangent such as <m>(0, -1)</m> and <m>(2, 7)</m>:
                    <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{7 - (-1)}{2 - 0} = \frac{8}{2} = 4</me>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A ball is thrown upwards such that its height <m>h</m> at time <m>t</m> is <m>h = 20t - 5t^2</m>. Use a graph to estimate the velocity of the ball at <m>t = 1</m> second.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The velocity at an instant is the gradient of the tangent at that time.
                    Plotting <m>h = 20t - 5t^2</m> and drawing a tangent at <m>(1, 15)</m>:
                    Estimated gradient should be around <m>10</m> m/s.
                </p>
                <image xml:id="img-ex-velocity-inst" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Projectile Motion with Tangent Line">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.25]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=5, ystep=5, xstep=1] (-1,0) grid (5,25);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$t$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-2) -- (0,25) node[above] {$h$};
                            \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:4] plot (\x, {20*\x - 5*\x*\x});
                            \draw[green!60!black, thick] (0, 5) -- (2, 25) node[right] {Tangent at $t=1$};
                            \filldraw (1,15) circle (2pt);
                            % Gradient triangle
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (0,5) -- (2,5);
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,5) -- (2,25) node[midway, right] {$\Delta h = 20$};
                            \filldraw (0,5) circle (2pt);
                            \filldraw (2,25) circle (2pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Sketch the graph of <m>y = 4 - x^2</m>. Estimate the gradient of the curve at <m>x = 1</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Plot <m>y = 4 - x^2</m> and draw a tangent at <m>(1, 3)</m>.
                    Picking points on the tangent like <m>(0, 5)</m> and <m>(2, 1)</m>:
                    <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{1 - 5}{2 - 0} = \frac{-4}{2} = -2</me>
                </p>
                <image xml:id="img-ex-quad-neg-inst" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Quadratic Function with Tangent Line">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-5) grid (3,5);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                            \draw[thick, blue, domain=-2.5:2.5] plot (\x, {4 - \x*\x});
                            \draw[green!60!black, thick] (-0.5, 6) -- (2.5, 0);
                            \filldraw (1,3) circle (2pt);
                            % Gradient triangle
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (0,5) -- (2,5);
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,5) -- (2,1) node[midway, right] {$\Delta y = -4$};
                            \filldraw (0,5) circle (2pt);
                            \filldraw (2,1) circle (2pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The number of bacteria <m>N</m> in a culture after <m>t</m> hours is given by <m>N = 2t^2 + 10</m>. Estimate the rate of growth of the bacteria at <m>t = 3</m> hours.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    At <m>t = 3</m>, <m>N = 2(3)^2 + 10 = 28</m>.
                    Draw a tangent at <m>(3, 28)</m> and pick points like <m>(2, 16)</m> and <m>(4, 40)</m>.
                    <me>\text{Rate} = \frac{40 - 16}{4 - 2} = \frac{24}{2} = 12 \text{ bacteria/hour}</me>
                </p>
                <image xml:id="img-ex-bacteria-inst" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Bacterial Growth with Tangent Line">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.1]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1, ystep=10, xstep=1] (0,0) grid (6,50);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,0) -- (6,0) node[right] {$t$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,0) -- (0,50) node[above] {$N$};
                            \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:4.4] plot (\x, {2*\x*\x + 10});
                            \draw[green!60!black, thick] (1, 4) -- (4.5, 46);
                            \filldraw (3,28) circle (3pt);
                            % Gradient triangle
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,16) -- (4,16) node[midway, below] {$\Delta t = 2$};
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (4,16) -- (4,40) node[midway, right] {$\Delta N = 24$};
                            \filldraw (2,16) circle (2pt);
                            \filldraw (4,40) circle (2pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Sketch the graph of <m>y = \frac{1}{2}x^2</m>. Estimate the instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = -2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    At <m>x = -2</m>, <m>y = 2</m>. Draw a tangent at <m>(-2, 2)</m>.
                    Pick points on the tangent such as <m>(0, -2)</m> and <m>(-3, 4)</m>.
                    <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{4 - (-2)}{-3 - 0} = \frac{6}{-3} = -2</me>
                </p>
                <image xml:id="img-ex-quad-neg-x-inst" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Quadratic_Function_Tangent_Line">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-4,-3) grid (2,6);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-4,0) -- (2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-3) -- (0,6) node[above] {$y$};
                            \draw[thick, blue, domain=-3.4:2] plot (\x, {0.5*\x*\x});
                            \draw[green!60!black, thick] (0.5, -3) -- (-3.5, 5);
                            \filldraw (-2,2) circle (2pt);
                            % Gradient triangle
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (0,-2) -- (-3,-2) node[midway, below] {$\Delta x = -3$};
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (-3,-2) -- (-3,4) node[midway, left] {$\Delta y = 6$};
                            \filldraw (0,-2) circle (2pt);
                            \filldraw (-3,4) circle (2pt);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For <m>f(x) = x^2</m>, estimate the instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = 3</m> by computing the average rate of change over <m>[3,\ 3+h]</m> for decreasing values of <m>h</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>h</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>f(3+h)</m></cell>
                            <cell>AROC <m>= \dfrac{f(3+h)-f(3)}{h}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.5</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.1</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.01</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <p>What value does the AROC appear to approach? This is the instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = 3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>h</m></cell><cell><m>f(3+h)</m></cell><cell>AROC <m>= 6+h</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell>1</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>7</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.5</cell><cell>12.25</cell><cell>6.5</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.1</cell><cell>9.61</cell><cell>6.1</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.01</cell><cell>9.0601</cell><cell>6.01</cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <p>The AROC approaches <m>6</m> as <m>h \to 0</m>. The instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = 3</m> is <m>6</m>.</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since <m>f(3+h) = (3+h)^2 = 9+6h+h^2</m> and <m>f(3)=9</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{AROC} = \frac{(9+6h+h^2)-9}{h} = \frac{6h+h^2}{h} = 6+h</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>As <m>h \to 0</m>, AROC <m>\to 6</m>. The instantaneous rate of change at <m>x=3</m> is <m>6</m>. Compare to the graphical estimate from the tangent: they should agree.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The position of a matatu along Ngong Road (in km from Nairobi) is given by <m>d(t) = 5t^2 + t</m>, where <m>t</m> is time in hours. The table below shows recorded positions near <m>t = 2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>t</m> (h)</cell>
                            <cell>1.9</cell><cell>1.95</cell><cell>2.0</cell><cell>2.05</cell><cell>2.1</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>d(t)</m> (km)</cell>
                            <cell>19.95</cell><cell>20.9625</cell><cell>22</cell><cell>23.0625</cell><cell>24.15</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Compute the average speed over <m>[1.9,\ 2.1]</m> and over <m>[1.95,\ 2.05]</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>What is your estimate for the instantaneous speed at exactly <m>t = 2</m>?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Both equal 21 km/h.</p></li>
                    <li><p>21 km/h.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{d(2.1)-d(1.9)}{2.1-1.9} \amp= \frac{24.15-19.95}{0.2} = \frac{4.2}{0.2} = 21 \text{ km/h}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\frac{d(2.05)-d(1.95)}{2.05-1.95} \amp= \frac{23.0625-20.9625}{0.1} = \frac{2.1}{0.1} = 21 \text{ km/h}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Both symmetric intervals give 21 km/h, so the instantaneous speed at <m>t=2</m> is <m>21</m> km/h.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of <m>f(x) = x^3 - 3x</m> is shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-3,-5) grid (3,5);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                            \draw[blue, thick, domain=-2.2:2.2, smooth] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x - 3*\x});
                            \node[blue] at (2.5, 4) {$f(x)$};
                            \filldraw (-1,2) circle (2pt) node[above left] {$(-1,2)$};
                            \filldraw (1,-2) circle (2pt) node[below right] {$(1,-2)$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>At <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 1</m>, the tangent to the curve is horizontal. What is the instantaneous rate of change at these points?</p></li>
                    <li><p>State whether the curve is rising or falling on each of the intervals <m>(-\infty,-1)</m>, <m>(-1,1)</m>, and <m>(1,\infty)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Estimate the instantaneous rate of change at <m>x = 2</m> by drawing a tangent and reading its gradient.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Zero at both points (horizontal tangent).</p></li>
                    <li><p>Rising on <m>(-\infty,-1)</m> and <m>(1,\infty)</m>; falling on <m>(-1,1)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Approximately <m>9</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>A horizontal tangent has slope zero, so the instantaneous rate of change is <m>0</m> at both <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=1</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><p>On <m>(-\infty,-1)</m>: the curve is <em>rising</em>.</p></li>
                                <li><p>On <m>(-1,1)</m>: the curve is <em>falling</em>.</p></li>
                                <li><p>On <m>(1,\infty)</m>: the curve is <em>rising</em> again.</p></li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>At <m>x=2</m>, <m>f(2)=8-6=2</m>. A tangent drawn at <m>(2,2)</m> gives a gradient of approximately <m>9</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A cyclist's distance from home (in km) is <m>s(t) = 3t^2</m>, where <m>t</m> is time in hours.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Plot the graph of <m>s(t)</m> for <m>0 \le t \le 3</m> and draw the tangent at <m>t = 2</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Estimate the cyclist's instantaneous speed at <m>t = 2</m> hours from your tangent.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Is the cyclist speeding up or slowing down as time increases? How does the graph show this?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Upward-opening parabola passing through <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(1,3)</m>, <m>(2,12)</m>, <m>(3,27)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Approximately <m>12</m> km/h.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Speeding up; the tangent becomes steeper as <m>t</m> increases.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Key values: <m>s(0)=0</m>, <m>s(1)=3</m>, <m>s(2)=12</m>, <m>s(3)=27</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Drawing a tangent at <m>(2, 12)</m> and reading two points — for example <m>(1, 0)</m> and <m>(3, 24)</m> — gives gradient <m>\dfrac{24-0}{3-1} = 12</m> km/h.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>The cyclist is speeding up. The tangent lines get steeper as <m>t</m> increases, meaning the instantaneous rate of change is growing.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A population of bacteria in a petri dish (in thousands) grows according to <m>P(t) = t^2 + 2t</m>, where <m>t</m> is time in hours.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Estimate the instantaneous rate of growth at <m>t = 1</m> by drawing a tangent to the graph of <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Estimate the instantaneous rate of growth at <m>t = 3</m> in the same way.</p></li>
                    <li><p>At which time is the population growing faster? By how much?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Approximately <m>4</m> thousand bacteria per hour.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Approximately <m>8</m> thousand bacteria per hour.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Faster at <m>t = 3</m>, by about <m>4</m> thousand bacteria per hour.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>At <m>t=1</m>, <m>P(1)=3</m>. A tangent drawn at <m>(1,3)</m> passes through approximately <m>(0,-1)</m> and <m>(2,7)</m>, giving gradient <m>\dfrac{7-(-1)}{2-0}=4</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>At <m>t=3</m>, <m>P(3)=15</m>. A tangent at <m>(3,15)</m> passes through approximately <m>(2,7)</m> and <m>(4,23)</m>, giving gradient <m>\dfrac{23-7}{4-2}=8</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>The population is growing faster at <m>t=3</m> (approximately 8 vs. 4 thousand bacteria per hour), by about 4 thousand bacteria per hour.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

